"Monogenetic" allows you to control brain cells using sound waves
The video clip shows how nematodes change direction when they are exposed to sound impulses.
Scientists have deduced genetically modified worms with the nervous system, which can be managed using impulse sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction at a moment when they are exposed to sound impulses that are too high for the human ear to hear.
The pulse is influenced by activation of neurons genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves.
More on topic: Researchers control brain activity using light
The scientists said that worms demonstrate the capabilities of a new technique called "monogenetic", the essence of which is the use of ultrasound to excite certain cells in the brain, heart and muscle, while the ultrasound source is located outside the body.
Srikant, Chalasani, research fellow at the Salk Institute, La JOLLA, California, told the Guardian that this technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation is an invasive procedure in which the human brain sends electrical impulses and which is used in the treatment of Parkinson's disease.
A nematode worm usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they started to react when placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles enhance the ultrasound waves, which then penetrate into the body of worms.
The amplified ultrasonic waves act on structures called "ion channels of TRP-4" found in the membranes of some cells of the worms.
Ultrasonic waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells that are associated with them, according to a report in Nature Communications.
To create nematodes that can be controlled through ultrasound, Chalasani made genetic modifications of worms, so their motor neurons used ion channel TRP-4.
During the application of ultrasound to influence modified organisms sound waves amplified microscopic bubbles and introduced into organisms, worms, modified by activating motor neurons.
This technique is similar to the one used in "optogenetic" - new direction, which allows scientists to turn on and off neurons with light pulses.
Chalasani argues that compared with this method sanogenetic may have some advantages.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the desired area of the brain via fiber, low-frequency ultrasonic waves can pass through body tissues, so shipping does not need to undergo inside the skull.
"We believe that to treat some neurological diseases clinical use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses will be able to make the human neurons are sensitive to the ultrasound signal," said Chalasani.
He added that, in addition, the technique can be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
