FedEx revenue was a mixed, lowering forecasts to 2016
FedEx reported disappointing results last quarter, and the giant delivery service has reduced the forecast of annual profit due to falling demand for trucking services and increased costs in its unit surface transport.
The company also said it plans to hire about 55,000 seasonal workers for the holidays.
At this same time last year FedEx announced that it will hire 50 000 temporary workers for the holidays.
Its shares fell about 2.5 percent in the previous auction in 45 minutes before the market opens on Wednesday.
FedEx Corp. said it plans to earn from $10,40 to $10.90 per fiscal year, which ends next may, which is 20 cents less than in the previous forecast.
Analysts expected $10,84 according to a survey by FactSet.
The forecast decline is observed despite the increase in rates on average by 4.9 per cent, which will come into force on 4 January, and the increase in charges for inland transportation of heavy or large cargoes, which begins in November.
The company said it still expects revenue growth compared to last year due to a reduction in costs, increase gross revenue and growth of online trading.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith said that the company "has worked steadily with weakness, compared with the forecast, economic conditions, particularly in production and world trade".
Plans to hire personnel during the holidays were announced on the day after the announcement of a competitor, UPS, that they plan to hire additional 95 000 employees, about as many as were recruited last year.
For the quarter ended August 31, FedEx earned $ 692 million, 6 percent higher than a year earlier.
Earnings per share amounted to 2,42 dollars, close to the forecast average of 2.44 dollars per share, Zacks Investment Research conducted a survey of 12 analysts.
Revenue increased by 5 %, to 12.3 billion dollars.
Six analysts polled by Zacks, was assumed to 12,23 billion.
FedEx has suffered in recent years from the downturn in the sector urgent international shipments that resulted in a lack of growth in gross income in her division Express transportation.
However, the boom of shopping on the Internet has sharply improved results at FedEx Ground.
In the last quarter of revenue from ground transport increased by 29 %, but operating income remained roughly unchanged because of increased costs of major items and insurance.
Division Express transportation received higher income due to a higher base rates, whereas in the cargo sector income fell because of higher costs for wages.
In the previous auction about an hour before the opening of the exchange the shares of FedEx fell $3,85, or 2.5 percent, to $150,15.
They closed Tuesday, falling 11 percent for the year and 17 percent below the record set on June 11.
The most anticipated in several years the meeting, the heads of the Federal reserve system will spend two days this week for 27-foot table out of Honduran mahogany, deciding whether it is time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly ten years.
At one end of the ornate meeting rooms of the height of two floors above them will hang a wall picture of the United States.
This card is a reminder that the Chairman of the Federal reserve system Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the economic interests of the country above all others.
The Central Bank got a double order of Congress: to maximize employment in the United States and to maintain stable prices.
But since the great recession, the heads of the Federal system has recognized that there is a third, unwritten order: financial stability.
This is the third instruction may be an unknown factor in almost predicted the decision will be announced on Thursday, to see whether the U.S. economy is to break away from the unprecedented stimulus provided by near zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
Even though most of the data show a steady growth of the economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets may hold already cautious of the heads of Federal systems from adding volatility by raising the base of the Federal funds rate - even by just a quarter percentage point.
"Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important consideration," said Lindsay M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"However, I think if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, which increased uncertainty around the global market was enough to give them an excuse to wait on," she said.
There is no consensus about what will make the Federal reserve system, which in itself provokes fluctuations of the financial market.
About half of the economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg, predicted a rise in interest rates this week.
Financial markets expect that the Federal system will hold that the key indicator shows only about 30-percent chance of a quick recovery.
This can lead to the collapse of the stock market, if the Federal system will raise your bid, provided that those who make decisions, will not soften the blow with a promise that the next increase will be soon.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones rose by 228,89 points, or 1.4%, to 16 599,85.
The rise was triggered by expectations that the persons defining the strategy of the Federal system, to remain unchanged this week, said John Lonski, the group's chief economist, Moody's Capital Markets Research.
"Be surprising if the Federal system will raise rates at this point of time," he said.
If the Federal reserve will do, "they have far to go in adopting its strategy to keep the financial markets in hand, so they did not panic".
Other experts argued that the rate increase could reassure the financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about how the Federal system.
Just a month ago, a Federal system seems to be inclined to raise the rate by 0.25 % this month, taking a first small step in a slow tightening of financial conditions that could confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in spring and early summer that it expects a rate hike this year, despite complaints from liberals about the need for greater economic progress.
Although the emergence of new jobs in August slowed the growth of the labor market was stable this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest rate in more than seven years, and nearly on the level that the Federal system is considered to be full employment.
Wage growth shows signs of accelerating.
And although inflation remains below the Central Bank planned annual index of 2%, the Federal system has said that a key reason was the temporary effect of a sharp fall in oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher stakes and need them, with the contraction of the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to shake at the end of last month, after China devalued its currency.
Average the Dow Jones industrial companies fell by as much as 16% compared to a record high in may, as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy could slow global growth.
The market partly recovered its position this month, and the Dow Jones is now about 10% below the may high value.
For the management of the Federal reserve system the indignation of the market further complicates the difficult calculations of the period of rising interest rates.
"In the absence of information about what happened in the financial markets and news about weakness in the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, they would have to tighten the screws at this meeting," said Steven D. Oliner, senior fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the Federal reserve system.
Now, he predicted, they will have to wait at least a month to get more control over the consequences.
"There is great uncertainty in what might be the consequences for the U.S. economy, and they have almost no reliable information on the recent events in China," said Oliner.
The health of the global economy is not included in the major preoccupations of the Federal system, and technically it should not be considered when making these decisions.
But essentially the Federal reserve became a world financial power.
The influence of the Central Bank in recent years has been huge.
Only one hint from the then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal reserve can "mute" their monetary expansion has caused the turmoil of the markets all over the world.
In a world where markets and economies increasingly intertwined, one would expect that the heads of the Federal reserve system will not only monitor the development of events elsewhere, but also to consult with representatives of other Central banks and with experts to better understand the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of Envestnet Inc - a company engaged in the global strategies of wealth management.
Jeffrey Lacker, President, Federal reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, said this month that "in the history of the Federal reserve system resulted in over-reacting to the movements of the financial market, which, it seems, are not bound to economic principles".
Lacker, a voting member of the influential Federal open market Committee, insisted on raising rates, in the cited decision 1998-99.
The financial crisis in Asia has led to the fact that the Federal system has reduced its base rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite the limited identifiable impact on growth in the U.S.," said Lacker.
A year later, the heads of the Federal system abolished this reduction.
The Federal reserve system should be put in the first place care about stability only in times of great crises such as the collapse of the market in 2008," said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Committee on rate-setting Bank of England.
Latest panic and comes close to that level, he said.
"You would certainly not want to be in a situation where you are afraid of the growth rates due to the fact that the markets are experiencing turmoil," said Posen, President of the Institute for international Economics. Peterson.
The law on Federal reserve system still has a dual mandate with no mention of financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should jump the gun.
