Diabetics with slight obesity, can help obesity surgery
Beneficial effects after bariatric surgery in people with slight obesity, diabetes type 2, can last at least five years, according to a new study.
Now, however, it is too early to say that diabetics with slight obesity, live longer after bariatric surgery than those who receive nonsurgical treatment.
"Mortality statistics is manifested not once," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert on obesity surgery, wrote about a new study in the column editor of JAMA Surgery.
Obesity surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses different techniques to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the capacity of organized utilization of food.
For several years bariatric surgery proved effective for the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but the main research was conducted among people with morbid obesity who have a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight for height, is considered normal if the value is from 18.5 to 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher suggests that a person overweight, and people with BMI above 30 are considered obese people.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from the Taiwan hospital Min-Sheng General used data collected from 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy with medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with moderate obesity.
Mean BMI in those who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of their participation in the study.
At the same time, the BMI of those who received nonsurgical treatment of diabetes, remained at around 29.
Among those who had surgery, completely recovered from diabetes 36%, and 28%.
In the group treated with medication, for comparison, complete recovery from diabetes was observed only in 1%, and a partial - only about 2%.
In addition, the blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol "in General were better in the surgical group," say the authors.
The researchers also monitored the levels of hemoglobin A1C in blood, which reflect the levels of blood sugar in the dynamics.
Hemoglobin A1c is better to keep below 7%, write the researchers.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the therapeutic group, however, it remained stable at about 8%.
But the best indicators of glycemic control, reflected good levels of hemoglobin A1c, not reduced the mortality rate in five years, according to the head of research of Dr. Chi-Cheng su and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results of two types of surgical treatment.
For the fifth year, in comparison with the group polchischa sleeve gastrectomy, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs. 14.2 kg), has achieved a larger decrease in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1C (3.1% vs. 2.1 percent) and was closer to complete remission of diabetes (46.9 per cent against 16.7 per cent).
Although the new study does not demonstrate the benefits of surgery in terms of survival after five years, there is evidence on the results of a study of people with overweight in Sweden that surgical treatment is indeed leading to the increase in life expectancy, according to Blackstone College of medicine in Phoenix, AZ, University of Arizona.
According to a Swedish study, for people with obesity, choosing bariatric intervention, the probability of dying during 15 years was about 29% lower compared with the group which used more traditional methods.
Although the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that this encourages people with BMI below 35 who are interested in this procedure.
"The report is very important because it argues that such surgery is safe in the group with low BMI, where there is no increased risk of mortality or renal diseases," she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors need to start seriously weight once the BMI of a patient is within the range between 27 to 30.
"I think we wait too long to get people to take this seriously," she said.
It seems to me that as soon as they accumulate the genetic changes that trigger in their bodies obesity and diabetes, pay it back very hard.
