Maintain Economy ― Nobel laureate: globalization
Print the globalization Processes should help reduce inequality in the world.
In fact, the situation is different, the difference in incomes in the emerging economies, on the contrary, grows.
Eric Maskin.
To fix this, you need to raise the level of education of low-skilled workers, says chief researcher of the International laboratory of choice and analysis of decisions of the HSE, Nobel prize winner in Economics in 2007 Eric Maskin.
In the last twenty years the world has experienced an unprecedented growth in global markets.
Trading borders between the countries became more open.
Proponents of globalization have predicted large benefits for developing economies.
"And these predictions largely came true," says the Maskin.
For example, China and India have received significant growth in GDP per capita.
However, not all so rosy.
It was expected that globalization would reduce the gap between the "haves" and "have-nots" in poorer countries, which manifests itself in the large income inequality, or rather - pay.
But in fact, this inequality has only increased, said Eric Maskin in his article "Why global markets have not reduced inequality in developing economies", published in The World Bank Economic Review, which was translated and quoted by ENI HSE.
Together with economist, Professor at Harvard University Michael Kremer Eric Maskin has developed an alternative theory that shows why increasing the difference in income in poor countries with the growth of globalization, reminds ENI HSE.
In the new global market specific processes occur.
To demonstrate, Maskin distinguishes four levels of professional development - A and B for rich countries, C and D for the poor.
After the globalization D professionals from poor countries do not have enough qualifications to cooperate with experts A and B from rich countries.
And if the staff level of the poor countries wages are growing thanks to cooperation with employees of B from the rich, then workers D growth either do not feel their pay is falling.
The final effect is that the internationalization of production will increase the gap in wages between the two categories of specialists in poor countries and consequently increased levels of inequality.
Kremer and E. Maskin proposed an amazingly beautiful model, alternative the Ricardian theory of comparative advantage.
It allows you to explain why globalization has led to income inequality, says Fuad Aleskerov, tenured Professor, head of the International laboratory of analysis and selection decisions, the head of the Department of mathematics of the HSE.
And like any powerful theory, I'm sure it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this area.
The solution, according to Eric Maskin is to improve the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as noted by scientist, have no money and companies not willing to pay for their education.
In such situation, a significant role may be played by governments, international agencies, NGOs and private foundations, says Maskin.
The scientist notes that the developed theory in any case does not call for a stop of process of globalization, which brought and brings fruit in the form of GDP growth of countries.
